  "issue_title": "[bug] llm/openai_compat: unbounded HTTP response reads can OOM genie-core",
  "issue_body": "### Summary\n\nThe hand-rolled OpenAI-compat LLM client reads HTTP bodies with no size cap:\n\n```rust\n// openai_compat.rs ~L585\u2013591\nlet mut buf = vec![0u8; content_length];  // trusts any Content-Length\n// ...\nread_to_string(&mut buf_reader, &mut response).await?;  // read until EOF\n```\n\n`http_get` always uses unbounded `read_to_string`. SSE streaming also accumulates `full_response` without a cap.\n\nContrast: `ha/client.rs` already has `read_http_response()` with `max_response_bytes`, capped `Content-Length`, and bounded EOF reads.\n\nA buggy or hostile LLM backend can grow RSS without limit and take down `genie-core`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Point `[services.llm]` at a mock TCP server on localhost.\n2. Return `HTTP/1.1 200 OK` with `Content-Length: 100000000` (or stream without closing).\n3. Trigger any chat/voice path using `OpenAiCompatClient`.\n4. Observe memory spike / OOM.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nMirror `ha/client.rs`: reject oversize `Content-Length`, cap EOF reads, cap SSE accumulation, return a clear error.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nUnbounded allocation / read until connection closes.\n\n### Hardware\n\nx86 dev host with mock TCP server sufficient\n\n### JetPack / L4T version\n\n_No response_\n\n### GenieClaw version / commit\n\n`main` @ `crates/genie-core/src/llm/openai_compat.rs`\n\n### Relevant logs\n\n```\n# Often silent OOM kill rather than a structured error\n```\n\n### Additional context\n\n**PR scope:** Bounded-read helper + refactor `http_post`/`http_get`/SSE + mock TCP tests (~120\u2013180 lines). Sized for substantive Rust AST changes (\u22655 gittensor token score).\n\n**Duplicate check**\n\n| Item | Relation |\n|------|----------|\n| **#181** (open) | LLM timeout only \u2014 not response byte cap |\n| **#203** (open) | Weather tool \u2014 same class, different path |\n| **#195** (closed) | Inbound HTTP bounded \u2014 not outbound LLM client |",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-27T22:42:35.000Z",
